        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>Sensitivity: Using the Halpha luminosities (Hancock et al. 2009), we estimated the SFR as given in Kennicutt 1998 and using this SFR value, estimated the FIR luminosities of the TDGs. Then from the CO - FIR correlation (Solomon &amp; Sage, 1988), we estimated the expected integrated intensities for our sources. Assuming a ~50 km/s line width and the emission to be distributed over ~20 beams (the number will vary between TDG1 and TDG2 depending on how compact the emission is), the expected line strength in CO (1-0) turns out to be  ~15 mJy/beam. Since this method of estimating the line strengths have several uncertainties, we also estimated the expected line strengths using a very similar object NGC 5291S from Braine et al. 2001. Depending on the extent of the emission as well as the total velocity width of the emission, we expect line strengths ~7 to 15 mJy. The peak strength can be higher as these estimates assume uniform distribution of flux over the area of the emission. To detect the signal at ~5sigma, in CO (1-0) our estimated rms per channel is 1.5 mJy. 

Spatial Resolution:  We will image each source  with a single pointing in both the frequencies. Mosaicing will not be needed.  The TDG in the tidal bridge has an angular size  ~0.8 arcmin. This is a linear structure with two adjacent Halpha detected clumps, each of 5arcsec in radius (Hancock et al., 2009), making it a ~ 20arcsec Halpha region. Since the FWHM for CO (2-1) will be slightly smaller than the entire TDG length, but will cover the Halpha clumps, we will image this source with  the pointing centre on one of the Halpha detected clump for both the frequencies. The spatial resolution requested is 3.0 arcsec, 650 pc at Arp 305 distance, a compromise, as the emission is expected to be weak.

Spectral Setup: A broad bandwidth and a  velocity resolution of ~5 km/s will be sufficient for our goals to detect the gas and also look for velocity gradients in the TDG in the bridge between NGC 4016/7 in CO (1-0). Therefore we request a bandwidth of 1875 MHz with velocity resolution of ~5 km/s  in CO (1-0). 

Therefore in total, including all overheads, we request observation time of 2.78 hours in CO (1-0).


</prj:justificationText>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
