    <prp:abstract>Low metallicities and thus low CO content of dwarf galaxies have severly limited the understanding of the molecular gas behaviour in these galaxies. Tidal dwarf galaxies (TDGs) form from the metal rich gas debris of interacting galaxies. CO content in TDGs is therefore fairly elevated compared to ordinary dwarfs formed from pristine gas. Thus TDGs provide the opportunity to study the molecular gas behaviour and star formation laws during the intial building of a dwarf galaxy, but with much higher molecular gas visibility.  While the enhanced CO content of TDGs assist molecular gas detection, they are still low mass objects requiring high spatial resolution and high sensitivity. These requirements make ALMA the ideal instrument for such studies.
 
We propose to observe two TDGs in the interacting debris of Arp 305. Our aim is to utilise ALMA CO (1-0) and (2-1) lines, HI from GMRT, along with archive Halpha and UV data to study the gas kinematics and SF laws in these dwarfs. Imaging these targets with a 3" spatial resolution, 5 km/s CO(1-0) and 10 km/s CO(2-1) spectral resolution and a 1.5 mJy rms per channel in both CO (1-0) and (2-1) will be sufficient to carryout this study.</prp:abstract>
